@cptnoremac upscaling is basically built into modern game development now. Its rare to see new games that dont rely on it in some way. Do you really think MachineGames wouldve pushed ray tracing always on in Indiana Jones if DLSSor any other upscalingdidnt exist to make it feasible? Or that wed see Nanites geometry without those specific optimizations?

On the Stable Diffusion side, it heavily depends on specialized GPU hardware like Tensor Cores and Cuda Cores, not just brute-force power. Without those specialized units, AI performance would tank. As for older games, most modern hardware can handle them with ease, and if theres a slowdown, its usually the game engine thats the issuenot raw GPU power.

Im not saying raw performance doesnt matterof course it does, especially when a game or application doesnt support upscaling. But as we keep pushing for bigger, faster GPUs, the performance gains arent as huge as they used to be. Thats why developers now lean heavily on AI and software optimizations instead of just throwing more teraflops at the problem. Physical and power constraints also limit how much you can scale up hardware, which is where DLSS, FSR, XeSS, and AI-focused cores come in to drive the next wave of performance in gaming and other GPU-heavy tasks.

